It is in both, the young man of letters, to whom Horace speaks naturally and freely on literary topics, assuming the mutual interest of (ach in the other's pursuits, but to whom he is disposed to hold up divine philosophy as a better medicine of the soul than either literature or the ambitions of practica] life.
